# NestJS Patterns

## Layer separation
```
GrpcController → Service → Repository → DB
     ↓               ↓
   DTOs          Domain Models  ←→  Mapper  ←→  DbTypes
```
- Controllers handle only request/response mapping. No business logic.
- Services own business logic; they never touch Knex directly.
- Repositories return domain models (via Mapper), never raw DB rows.

## Mappers
- Every entity has a `*.mapper.ts` with static `toDomain(db: UserDb): UserDomainModel` and `toDb(domain: UserDomainModel): UserDb`.
- Mappers are stateless — do not inject them; use static methods.

## DTOs
- One DTO file per use-case (e.g. `login.dto.ts`, `register.dto.ts`).
- Use `class-validator` + `class-transformer`. Nest DTOs for complex inputs (e.g. `DeviceInfoDto` inside `LoginDto`).

## gRPC controllers
- Decorated with `@GrpcMethod('ServiceName', 'MethodName')`.
- Accept proto-generated request type, return proto-generated response type.
- Delegate to a use-case service immediately; no logic in the controller body.

## Guards & decorators
- Service-to-service auth: `LocalIdentityGuard` + `@RequirePermission(...)` from `@gomin/service-identity`.
- Do not write custom JWT parsing in app code — always go through the shared guard.

## Config
- All env vars validated via Joi `validationSchema` in `ConfigModule.forRoot`.
- Compose schemas: `validationSchema: knexDatabaseValidationSchema.concat(appSchema)`.
